prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Because we observe 12CO(2-1) and 13CO(2-1) simultaneously, the tolerance of the setting is very limited as shown in knowledgebase on Science portal. We set the parameters so that the OT doesnt issue any errors or warnings. The velocity bandwidth of 153km/s is needed to cover the wide spectra of strong outflow from the luminous YSOs. H30alpha and SiO(5-4) line are expected to have much wider band-width than CO lines, and we set the band width of 1875MHz with a velocity resolution of 2.5km/s for H30alpha and 1.56km/s for SiO(5-4). The choice of the band-width, 1875MHz is to increase the continuum sensitivity.

An angular resolution of 1"(0.24pc) is definitely needed to detect outflows and detailed structures of molecular gas as was shown in the Cycle 1 observations. We request one pointing per source; the primary beam size in Figure 1 indicates that one pointing can observe an area large enough to cover the molecular gas related to the YSO. We dont use ACA because we will carry out single pointing observations and because our focus here is the enhanced emission toward the YSOs (Figure 1 only uses 12m array data).

The maximum temperatures of 12CO(2-1), 13CO(2-1) and C18O(2-1) are expected to be ~50K, 20K, a few K, respectively, from our experience of Cycle 1 N159W/E observations. The typical line width is 5-10km/s, and we would like to set the sensitivity of 0.4K at 0.4km/s resolution to investigate the velocity structure of molecular gas. Cycle 1 N159W/E observations also shows the typical continuum flux of a few mJy, and the current 0.1mJy is good enough to detect the emission. H30alpha is also detected with the past observations whose sensitivity is similar. The detection of SiO(5-4) is a bit uncertain, but we expect to have strong emission in regions with strong shocks.

prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Band 3: 13CO, C18O(1-0), CS(2-1), H40alpha, and continuum

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: The bandwidth of 160km/s is wide enough to cover the specra. We set velocity resolution of 0.2km/s to precisely investigate the dynamics of the molecular gas where the line intensity is high. H40 alpha is expected to have much wider band-width than CO lines, and we set the band width of 1875MHz with a velocity resolution of 3.4km/s. The choice of the band-width, 1875MHz is to increase the continuum sensitivity.

Although the higher spatial resolution will be achieved at Band 6, we need at least 2" to resolve the molecular clouds structure especially of dense cores. We request one pointing per source; the primary beam size in Figure 1 indicates that one pointing can observe an area large enough to cover the molecular gas related to the YSO. We dont use ACA because we will carry out single pointing observations and because our focus here is the enhanced emission toward the YSOs (Figure 1 only uses 12m array data).

The maximum temperatures of 13CO(1-0), C18O(1-0) and CS(2-1) are expected to be ~15K, a few K, 5 K, respectively, from our experience of Cycle 1 N159W/E observations. The typical line width is 5-10km/s, and we would like to set the sensitivity of 0.4K at 0.4km/s resolution to investigate the velocity structure of molecular gas. Cycle 1 N159W/E observations also shows the typical continuum flux of a few mJy, and the current 0.06mJy is good enough to detect the emission. H40alpha is also detected with the past observations whose sensitivity is similar.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: This proposal aims at observing the brightest 45 high-mass YSOs, whose luminosity is a few 10^4 to 10^6 Lo, in the Large Magellanic Cloud in order to investigate the evolution of high-mass protostars in terms of the properties of the surrounding material. Our Cycle 1 observation toward N159W/E detected many features related to high-mass star formation; molecular outflows detected in 12CO(2-1), an indication of cloud-cloud collision as a formation mechanism of high-mass YSOs, the dense gas dissipation, the detection of radio recombination lines, and so on. These are thus found to be good tracers of the evolutionary status of high-mass YSOs and of the effect of the YSOs to the surrounding environments. The target lines we use are 12CO(2-1), 13CO(2-1), C18O(2-1), 13CO(1-0), C18O(1-0), CS(2-1), SiO(5-4), H30alpha, and H40alpha as well as in continuum in Band 6 and Band 3. Analysis of the proposed gas/dust data in combination with our expert knowledge of the LMC's high-mass YSO population and molecular gas distribution on larger scales will allow us to identify the conditions that lead to high-mass YSO formation and estimate the dissipation timescale of the progenitor clouds.
